%S A091508 1,2,111,7,5,3,25,22,25,111,111,4,7,5,5,6,22,25,22,9,111,25,25,4,111,
%T A091508 111,11,111,9,7,6,8,19,5,6,19,9,22,22,111,8,22,19,9,9,111,111,111,111,
%U A091508 25,15,11,9,111,8,111,16,11,7,5,9,9,9,15,111,6,111,10,7,19,19,19,9,6,25
%N A091508 Least k such that b(k) = 1, where b(1) = n and b(k+1) = b(k)+k+1 if gcd(k+1, b(k)) = 1 or else b(k)/gcd(k+1, b(k)).
%C A091508 I conjecture a(n) always exists. That means sequence (b(k)) becomes ultimately regular for any n. i.e. there is always k0 such that b(k0) = 1, so b(k0+1) = b(k0) + k0 = k0 + 1 since gcd(k0, b(k0)) = 1 and gcd(k0+1, b(k0+1)) = k0+1 implies b(k0+2) = b(k0+1)/(k0+1) = 1 and from that point k0 sequence (b(k)) continues : 1, k0+1, 1, k0+2, 1, k0+3,1,... and is "regular".
%C A091508 From _Sam Chapman_, Mar 30 2026: (Start)
%C A091508 a(k!) = k for all k. As such, every positive integer appears in this sequence at least once. 1, 2, and 3 each appear only once, whereas every other number appears more than once.
%C A091508 If m > k!, then a(m) > k, if a(m) exists. As such, there are a finite amount of values n such that a(n) = k.
%C A091508 Benoit's conjecture is true for all n <= 10^15. (End)
%H A091508 Michel Marcus, <a href="/A091508/b091508.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%F A091508 a(n!) = n for all n >= 1. - _Sam Chapman_, Mar 30 2026
%e A091508 For n = 1 we have b(1) = 1, hence a(1) = 1.
%e A091508 For n = 2 we have b(1) = 2, then for k = 1 we have gcd(2, b(1)) = 2 and therefore b(2) = b(1)/2 = 1, thus a(2) = 2.
%e A091508 For n = 6 we have b(1) = 6, then for k = 1 we have gcd(2, b(1)) = 2 whence b(2) = 6/2 = 3. Then for k = 2 we have gcd(3, b(2)) = 3 whence b(3) = 3/3 = 1, and a(6) = 3. Similarly, for all n = m!, b(k) = m!/k! and a(n) = m.
%o A091508 (PARI) a(n)=if(n<0,0,s=1;b=n;while(b>1,s++;b=if(gcd(s,b)-1,b/gcd(b,s),b+s));s)
%o A091508 (PARI) apply( {A091508(n)=for(k=2,oo, if(n==1, return(k-1), gcd(n,k)>1, n\=gcd(n,k), n+=k))}, [1..99]) \\ _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 10 2026
%K A091508 nonn,changed
%O A091508 1,2
%A A091508 _Benoit Cloitre_, Mar 03 2004
